Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/http-routes.ts (await savePluginSettings before performConfigReload)

Context:
In handlePluginSettings (http-routes.ts around line 669-693), the current code:
  state.pluginSettings[body.plugin] = body.settings;
  savePluginSettings(state, { ...state.pluginSettings }).catch(() => {});  // fire-and-forget!
  try {
    await performConfigReload(state, sessionServers, transports);
  } catch (err) {
    log.warn('Reload after settings change failed:', err);
  }

The same race: savePluginSettings is fire-and-forget, then performConfigReload runs and overwrites state.pluginSettings from disk.

Changes:
Replace the fire-and-forget call with an awaited one:
  - Remove: savePluginSettings(state, { ...state.pluginSettings }).catch(() => {});
  - Add before performConfigReload: await savePluginSettings(state, { ...state.pluginSettings }).catch(() => {});

Constraints:
- savePluginSettings is already imported at the top of http-routes.ts
- The error is caught with .catch(() => {}) so a disk write failure is non-fatal — this is intentional
- The change is ONLY in handlePluginSettings, not in any other function

Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/http-routes.ts (add type validation for non-url settings)

Context:
In handlePluginSettings (http-routes.ts around line 632-666), the current validation loop:
  for (const [key, definition] of Object.entries(registeredPlugin.configSchema)) {
    if (definition.type !== 'url') continue;  // <-- ONLY validates url type
    // validates url...
  }

In handleConfigSetPluginSettings (extension-handlers.ts around line 664-730), the validation loop validates all types:
  for (const [key, definition] of Object.entries(schema)) {
    const value = settingsObj[key];
    if (definition.required && (value === undefined || value === null || value === '')) {
      errors.push(`Setting "${key}" is required`);
    }
    switch (definition.type) {
      case 'url': { /* existing url validation */ }
      case 'string': { if (typeof value !== 'string') errors.push(...); }
      case 'number': { if (typeof value !== 'number') errors.push(...); }
      case 'boolean': { if (typeof value !== 'boolean') errors.push(...); }
      case 'select': { if (typeof value !== 'string' || !definition.options.includes(value)) errors.push(...); }
    }
  }

Changes:
In handlePluginSettings (http-routes.ts), extend the validation loop to add cases for string, number, boolean, and select type fields. Reuse the exact same validation messages as handleConfigSetPluginSettings in extension-handlers.ts.

The existing url-type validation block is around lines 636-663. Add the new cases after it (inside the for loop, before the closing brace).

Note: required field validation (checking for undefined/null/empty string) is already handled for url type. Add the same required check for all other types.

When errors.length > 0, return Response.json({ ok: false, error: errors.join('; ') }, { status: 400 }).

Constraints:
- Only change handlePluginSettings in http-routes.ts
- Do NOT change handleConfigSetPluginSettings in extension-handlers.ts
- The url-type validation loop that already exists must remain intact
